<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="385" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1687,2001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,405,1687,1712]" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale" box="[464,756,1687,1712]" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" refString="Dondale, C. D. &amp; Redner, J. H. (1981) Classification of two North American species of Pirata, with a description of a new genus (Araneae, Lycosidae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 170, 106 - 110." type="journal article" year="1981">Dondale &amp; Redner (1981)</bibRefCitation>
for the full diagnosis). Carapace with a characteristic pattern (
<figureCitation box="[159,230,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[177,1430,195,1730]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[177,1462,195,1735]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Female of Trebacosa marxi (Stone, 1890). 1 habitus, dorsal view; 2 epigyne, ventral view; 3 cleared epigyne, ventral view; 4 vulva, dorsal view. Scale bars are 1.0 mm for habitus, 0.25 mm for vulva images." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242300/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Figs 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[244,290,1724,1749]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 7" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1960,1982]" captionTargetBox="[151,1418,1016,1832]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,999,1938]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 7. Trebacosa europaea Szinetár &amp; Kancsal, 2007. 5 female from Hungary, from the type locality, habitus, dorsal view; 6 female from Greece, dorsal view; 7 female from France, dorsal view. Scale bars are 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242301/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">5–7</figureCitation>
): three parallel white lines, which do not touch. This is similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Sundevall, 1833" authorityName="Sundevall" authorityYear="1833" box="[1125,1389,1724,1749]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pirata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1125,1197,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Pirata</emphasis>
Sundevall, 1833
</taxonomicName>
, but those have the white line converging in the thoracic region. The short sperm ducts are similar in the genera 
<taxonomicName box="[1357,1428,1761,1784]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pirata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1357,1428,1761,1784]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Pirata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Roewer, 1960" authorityName="Roewer" authorityYear="1960" box="[151,418,1796,1821]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Piratula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,244,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Piratula</emphasis>
Roewer, 1960
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[483,599,1796,1821]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Trebacosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[483,599,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Trebacosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[759,875,1796,1821]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Trebacosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[759,875,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Trebacosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1312,1383,1797,1820]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pirata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1312,1383,1797,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Pirata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,244,1831,1856]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Piratula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,244,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Piratula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the position of the vulval chamber relative to the head of spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[1099,1216,1831,1856]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 18" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1843,1865]" captionTargetBox="[211,1367,271,1791]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[211,1369,193,1828]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 18. Trebacosa europaea Szinetár &amp; Kancsal, 2007 female genitalia. 8 – 9. Diagnostic drawings of a female from the type locality: 8 epigyne, ventral view, 9 vulva, dorsal view. 10 – 18. Comparision images from different localities. 10 – 12, 16. Female from Hungary, type locality: 10 epigyne, ventral view, 11 cleared epigyne, ventral view, 12 vulva, dorsal view, 16 vulva, dorsal view, via compound microscope, 13 – 15. Female from Greece: 13 epigyne, ventral view, 14 cleared epigyne, ventral view, 15 vulva, dorsal view, 17 – 18. Female from France: 17 cleared epigyne, ventral view; 18 female vulva, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242302/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Figs 9, 16</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1229,1260,1832,1856]" captionStart="FIGURES 19 – 22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1202,1224]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1181]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1181]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 19 – 22. SEM images of Trebacosa europaea Szinetár &amp; Kancsal, 2007 female genitalia from the type locality, Hungary. 19 epigyne, ventral view; 20 vulva, dorsal view; 3 left structures, dorsal view; 4 closeup of the pores on the head of spermatheca, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242303/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">21</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName box="[1313,1429,1831,1856]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Trebacosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1313,1429,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Trebacosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the HS is ectal and the VC is mesal, whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[692,785,1868,1893]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Piratula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[692,785,1868,1893]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Piratula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[841,913,1869,1892]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pirata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[841,913,1869,1892]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Pirata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the HS is positioned mesal relative to the VC. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,267,1903,1928]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Trebacosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,267,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Trebacosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is seemingly unique by possessing the primary pores at the basis of the HS (Luis Piacentini – 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">pers comm.</emphasis>
). Males of 
<taxonomicName box="[358,474,1940,1965]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Trebacosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[358,474,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="385">Trebacosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by the large angular median apophysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale" box="[1149,1431,1940,1965]" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" refString="Dondale, C. D. &amp; Redner, J. H. (1981) Classification of two North American species of Pirata, with a description of a new genus (Araneae, Lycosidae). Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 170, 106 - 110." type="journal article" year="1981">Dondale &amp; Redner 1981</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Dondale" box="[151,314,1976,2001]" pageId="1" pageNumber="385" refString="Dondale, C. D. (2005) Lycosidae. In: Ubick, D., Paquin, P., Cushing, P. &amp; Roth, V. (Eds.), Spiders of North America: an identification manual. American Arachnological Society, pp 164 - 170." type="book chapter" year="2005">Dondale 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
